# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-interfaces
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:hardware-interfaces/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] A **general-purpose input/output** (**GPIO**) is an uncommitted digital signal pin on an integrated circuit or electronic circuit (e.g.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] MCUs/MPUs) board that can be used as an input or output, or both, and is controllable by software.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs have no predefined purpose and are unused by default.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] If used, the purpose and behavior of a GPIO is defined and implemented by the designer of higher assembly-level circuitry: the circuit board designer in the case of integrated circuit GPIOs, or system integrator in the case of board-level GPIOs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Integrated circuit (IC) GPIOs are implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some ICs provide GPIOs as a primary function whereas others include GPIOs as a convenient "accessory" to some other primary function.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Examples of the former include the Intel 8255, which interfaces 24 GPIOs to a parallel communication bus, and various GPIO *expander* ICs, which interface GPIOs to serial communication buses such as I²C and SMBus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] An example of the latter is the Realtek ALC260 IC, which provides eight GPIOs along with its main function of audio codec.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Microcontroller ICs usually include GPIOs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Depending on the application, a microcontroller's GPIOs may comprise its primary interface to external circuitry or they may be just one type of I/O used among several, such as analog signal I/O, counter/timer, and serial communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] In some ICs, particularly microcontrollers, a GPIO pin may be capable of other functions than GPIO.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Often in such cases it is necessary to configure the pin to operate as a GPIO (vis-à-vis its other functions) in addition to configuring the GPIO's behavior.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some microcontroller devices (e.g., Microchip dsPIC33 family) incorporate internal signal routing circuitry that allows GPIOs to be programmatically mapped to device pins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) extend this ability by allowing GPIO pin mapping, instantiation and architecture to be programmatically controlled.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some microcontrollers and FPGAs allow a device to offload the task of bit-banging the GPIO to a separate device, the programmable input/output controller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Many circuit boards expose board-level GPIOs to external circuitry through integrated electrical connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Usually, each such GPIO is accessible via a dedicated connector pin.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Like IC-based GPIOs, some boards merely include GPIOs as a convenient, auxiliary resource that augments the board's primary function, whereas in other boards the GPIOs are the central, primary function of the board.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some boards, which are classified usually as multi-function I/O boards, are a combination of both; such boards provide GPIOs along with other types of general-purpose I/O.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs are also found on embedded controller boards and Single board computers such as Arduino, BeagleBone, and Raspberry Pi.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] While some board-level GPIOs are simple connections to IC pins, many are given abilities which IC-based GPIOs usually lack.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] For example, Schmitt-trigger inputs, high-current output drivers, optical isolators, or combinations of these, may be used to buffer and condition the GPIO signals and to protect board circuitry.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Also, higher-level functions are sometimes implemented, such as input debounce, input signal edge detection, and pulse-width modulation (PWM) output.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs are used in a diverse variety of applications, limited only by the electrical and timing specifications of the GPIO interface and the ability of software to interact with GPIOs in a sufficiently timely manner.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs usually employ standard logic levels and cannot supply significant current to output loads.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] When followed by an appropriate high-current output buffer (or mechanical or solid-state relay), a GPIO may be used to control high-power devices such as lights, solenoids, heaters, and motors (e.g., fans and blowers).
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Similarly, an input buffer, relay or opto-isolator is often used to translate an otherwise incompatible signal (e.g., high voltage) to the logic levels required by a GPIO.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Integrated circuit GPIOs are commonly used to control or monitor other circuitry (including other ICs) on a board.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Examples of this include enabling and disabling the operation of (or power to) other circuitry, reading the states of on-board switches and configuration shunts, and driving light-emitting diode (LED) status indicators.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] In the latter case, a GPIO can, in many cases, supply enough output current to directly power an LED without using an intermediate buffer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Multiple GPIOs are sometimes used together as a bit banging communication interface.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Taken to the extreme, this method may be used to implement an entire parallel bus, thus allowing communication with bus-oriented ICs or circuit boards.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Although GPIOs are fundamentally digital in nature, they are often used to control analog processes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] For example, a GPIO may be used to control motor speed, light intensity, or temperature.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Usually, this is done via PWM, in which the duty cycle of the GPIO output signal determines the effective magnitude of the process control signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] For example, when controlling light intensity, the light may be dimmed by reducing the GPIO duty cycle.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some analog processes require an analog control voltage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] In such cases, it may be feasible to connect a GPIO, which is operated as a PWM output, to an RC filter to create a simple, low cost digital-to-analog converter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] In some cases, they are simple—a group of pins that can switch as a group to either input or output.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] In others, each pin can be set up to accept or source different logic voltages, with configurable drive strengths and pull ups/downs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Input and output voltages are usually, but not always, limited to the supply voltage of the device with the GPIOs, and may be damaged by greater voltages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] A GPIO pin's state may be exposed to the software developer through one of a number of different interfaces, such as a memory-mapped I/O peripheral, or through dedicated IO port instructions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] Some GPIOs have 5 V tolerant inputs: even when the device has a low supply voltage (such as 2 V), the device can accept 5 V without damage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/general-purpose-input-output] A GPIO port is a group of GPIO pins (often 8 pins, but it may be fewer) arranged in a group and controlled as a group.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The I2C bus can be found in a wide range of electronics applications where simplicity and low manufacturing cost are more important than speed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] PC components and systems which involve I2C include serial presence detect (SPD) EEPROMs on dual in-line memory modules (DIMMs) and Extended Display Identification Data (EDID) for monitors via VGA, DVI, and HDMI connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A particular strength of I2C is the capability of a microcontroller to control a network of device chips with just two general-purpose I/O pins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Many other bus technologies used in similar applications, such as Serial Peripheral Interface Bus (SPI), require more pins and signals to connect multiple devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] System Management Bus (SMBus), defined by Intel and Duracell in 1994, is a subset of I2C, defining a stricter usage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One purpose of SMBus is to promote robustness and interoperability.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Accordingly, modern I2C systems incorporate some policies and rules from SMBus, sometimes supporting both I2C and SMBus, requiring only minimal reconfiguration either by commanding or output pin use.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] System management for PC systems uses SMBus, whose pins are allocated in both conventional PCI and PCI Express connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In the European Patent EP0051332B1 Ad P.M.M.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Moelands and Herman Schutte are named as inventors of the I2C bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Both were working in 1980 as development engineers in the central application laboratory CAB of Philips in Eindhoven, where the I2C bus was developed as "Two-wire bus-system comprising a clock wire and a data wire for interconnecting a number of stations".
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The US patent was granted under number US 4689740A .
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The internal development name of the bus was first COMIC, which was later changed to I2C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The patent was transferred to Koninklijke Philips NV.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C patents and specifications used the terms *master/slave* between 1980 and 2021.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In 2021, revision 7 of the I2C specification changed the terms to *controller/target*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The technical definitions of such devices, and their roles on an I2C bus, remain unchanged.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C uses only two signals: serial data line (SDA) and serial clock line (SCL).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Both are bidirectional and pulled up with resistors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Typical voltages used are +5 V or +3.3 V, although systems with other voltages are permitted.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The I2C reference design has a 7-bit address space, with a rarely used 10-bit extension.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Some vendors report 8-bit and 11-bit addresses instead, as the lowest bit in the first address byte is used to differentiate between write and read commands.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Common I2C bus speeds are the 100 kbit/s *standard mode* and the 400 kbit/s *fast mode*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] There is also a 10 kbit/s *low-speed mode*, but arbitrarily low clock frequencies are also allowed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Later revisions of I2C can host more nodes and run at faster speeds (400 kbit/s *fast mode*, 1 Mbit/s *fast mode plus*, 3.4 Mbit/s *high-speed mode*, and 5 Mbit/s *ultra-fast mode*).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] These speeds are more widely used on embedded systems than on PCs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Note that the bit rates are quoted for the transfers between controller (master) and target (slave) without clock stretching or other hardware overhead.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Protocol overheads include a target address and perhaps a register address within the target device, as well as per-byte ACK/NACK bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Thus the actual transfer rate of user data is lower than those peak bit rates alone would imply.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, if each interaction with a target inefficiently allows only 1 byte of data to be transferred, the data rate will be less than half the peak bit rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The number of nodes that can exist on a given I2C bus is limited by the address space and also by the total bus capacitance of 400 pF, which restricts practical communication distances to a few meters.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The relatively high impedance and low noise immunity require a common ground potential, which again restricts practical use to communication within the same PC board or small system of boards.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The aforementioned reference design is a bus with a clock (SCL) and data (SDA) lines with 7-bit addressing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The bus is a multi-controller bus, which means that any number of controller nodes can be present.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Additionally, controller and target roles may be changed between messages (after a STOP is sent).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In addition to 0 and 1 data bits, the I2C bus allows special START and STOP signals, which act as message delimiters and are distinct from the data bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller is initially in controller transmit mode by sending a START followed by the 7-bit address of the target it wishes to communicate with, which is finally followed by a single bit representing whether it wishes to write (0) to or read (1) from the target.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If the target exists on the bus then it will respond with an ACK bit (active low for acknowledged) for that address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller then continues in either transmit or receive mode (according to the read/write bit it sent), and the target continues in the complementary mode (receive or transmit, respectively).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The address and the data bytes are sent most significant bit first.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The start condition is indicated by a high-to-low transition of SDA with SCL high; the stop condition is indicated by a low-to-high transition of SDA with SCL high.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] All other transitions of SDA take place with SCL low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If the controller wishes to write to the target, then it repeatedly sends a byte with the target sending an ACK bit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If the controller wishes to read from the target, then it repeatedly receives a byte from the target, the controller sending an ACK bit after every byte except the last one.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] An I2C transaction may consist of multiple messages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller terminates a message with a STOP condition if this is the end of the transaction or it may send another START condition to retain control of the bus for another message (a "combined format" transaction).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In a combined transaction, each read or write begins with a START and the target address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The START conditions after the first are also called *repeated START* bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Repeated STARTs are not preceded by STOP conditions, which is how targets know that the next message is part of the same transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Any given target will only respond to certain messages, as specified in its product documentation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Pure I2C systems support arbitrary message structures.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] SMBus is restricted to nine of those structures, such as *read word N* and *write word N*, involving a single target.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] PMBus extends SMBus with a *Group* protocol, allowing multiple such SMBus transactions to be sent in one combined message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The terminating STOP indicates when those grouped actions should take effect.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, one PMBus operation might reconfigure three power supplies (using three different I2C target addresses), and their new configurations would take effect at the same time: when they receive that STOP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] With only a few exceptions, neither I2C nor SMBus define message semantics, such as the meaning of data bytes in messages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Message semantics are otherwise product-specific.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Those exceptions include messages addressed to the I2C *general call* address (0x00) or to the SMBus *Alert Response Address*; and messages involved in the SMBus *Address Resolution Protocol* (ARP) for dynamic address allocation and management.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In practice, most targets adopt request-response control models, where one or more bytes following a write command are treated as a command or address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Those bytes determine how subsequent written bytes are treated or how the target responds on subsequent reads.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Most SMBus operations involve single-byte commands.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One specific example is the 24C32 type EEPROM, which uses two request bytes that are called Address High and Address Low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] (Accordingly, these EEPROMs are not usable by pure SMBus hosts, which support only single-byte commands or addresses.) These bytes are used for addressing bytes within the 32 kbit (or 4 kB) EEPROM address space.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The same two-byte addressing is also used by larger EEPROMs, like the 24C512, which stores 512 kbits (or 64 kB).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Writing data to and reading from these EEPROMs uses a simple protocol: the address is written, and then data is transferred until the end of the message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The data transfer part of the protocol can cause trouble on the SMBus, since the data bytes are not preceded by a count, and more than 32 bytes can be transferred at once.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C EEPROMs smaller than 32 kbit, like the 2 kbit 24C02, are often used on the SMBus with inefficient single-byte data transfers to overcome this problem.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] After the START, the controller sends the chip's bus address with the direction bit clear (*write*), then sends the two-byte address of data within the EEPROM and then sends data bytes to be written starting at that address, followed by a STOP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When writing multiple bytes, all the bytes must be in the same 32-byte page.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] While it is busy saving those bytes to memory, the EEPROM will not respond to further I2C requests.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] To read starting at a particular address in the EEPROM, a combined message is used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] After a START, the controller first writes that chip's bus address with the direction bit clear (*write*) and then the two bytes of EEPROM data address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] It then sends a (repeated) START and the EEPROM's bus address with the direction bit set (*read*).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The EEPROM will then respond with the data bytes beginning at the specified EEPROM data address — a combined message: first a write, then a read.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller issues an ACK after each read byte except the last byte, and then issues a STOP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The EEPROM increments the address after each data byte transferred; multi-byte reads can retrieve the entire contents of the EEPROM using one combined message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] At the physical layer, both SCL and SDA lines are an open-drain (MOSFET) or open-collector (BJT) bus design, thus a pull-up resistor is needed for each line.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A logic "0" is output by pulling the line to ground, and a logic "1" is output by letting the line float (output high impedance) so that the pull-up resistor pulls it high.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This wiring allows multiple nodes to connect to the bus without short circuits from signal contention.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] High-speed systems (and some others) may use a current source instead of a resistor to pull up only SCL or both SCL and SDA, to accommodate higher bus capacitance and enable faster rise times.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] An important consequence of this is that multiple nodes may be driving the lines simultaneously.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If *any* node is driving the line low, it will be low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Nodes that are trying to transmit a logical one (i.e., letting the line float high) can detect this and conclude that another node is active at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When used on SCL, this is called *clock stretching* and is a flow-control mechanism for targets.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When used on SDA, this is called arbitration and ensures that there is only one transmitter at a time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] To start a transaction, SDA is pulled low while SCL remains high.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] It is illegal to transmit a stop marker by releasing SDA to float high again (although such a "void message" is usually harmless), so the next step is to pull SCL low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Except for the start and stop signals, the SDA line only changes while the clock is low; transmitting a data bit consists of pulsing the clock line high while holding the data line steady at the desired level.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] While SCL is low, the transmitter (initially the controller) sets SDA to the desired value and (after a small delay to let the value propagate) lets SCL float high.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller then waits for SCL to actually go high; this will be delayed by the finite rise time of the SCL signal (the RC time constant of the pull-up resistor and the parasitic capacitance of the bus) and may be additionally delayed by a target's clock stretching.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Once SCL is high, the controller waits a minimum time (4 μs for standard-speed I2C) to ensure that the receiver has seen the bit, then pulls it low again.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] After every 8 data bits in one direction, an "acknowledge" bit is transmitted in the other direction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The transmitter and receiver switch roles for one bit, and the original receiver transmits a single "0" bit (ACK) back.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Only the SDA line changes direction during acknowledge bits; the SCL is always controlled by the controller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One of the more significant features of the I2C protocol is clock stretching.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] An addressed target device may hold the clock line (SCL) low after receiving (or sending) a byte, indicating that it is not yet ready to process more data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller that is communicating with the target may not finish the transmission of the current bit, but must wait until the clock line actually goes high.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If the target is clock-stretching, the clock line will still be low (because the connections are open-drain).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The same is true if a second, slower, controller tries to drive the clock at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The controller must wait until it observes the clock line going high, and an additional minimal time (4 μs for standard 100 kbit/s I2C) before pulling the clock low again.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Although the controller may also hold the SCL line low for as long as it desires (this is not allowed since Rev.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] 6 of the protocol – subsection 3.1.1), the term "clock stretching" is normally used only when targets do it.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Although in theory any clock pulse may be stretched, generally it is the intervals before or after the acknowledgment bit that are used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, if the target is a microcontroller, its I2C interface could stretch the clock after each byte, until the software decides whether to send a positive acknowledgment or a NACK.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Clock stretching is the only time in I2C where the target drives SCL.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Many targets do not need to clock stretch and thus treat SCL as strictly an input with no circuitry to drive it.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Some controllers, such as those found inside custom ASICs, may not support clock stretching; often these devices will be labeled as a "two-wire interface" and not I2C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] To maximize bus throughput, SMBus places limits on how far clocks may be stretched.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Hosts and targets adhering to those limits cannot block access to the bus for more than a short time, which is not a guarantee made by pure I2C systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Every controller monitors the bus for start and stop bits and does not start a message while another controller is keeping the bus busy.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] However, two controllers may start transmission at about the same time; in this case, arbitration occurs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Target transmit mode can also be arbitrated when a controller addresses multiple targets, but this is less common.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In contrast to protocols (such as Ethernet) that use random back-off delays before issuing a retry, I2C has a deterministic arbitration policy.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Each transmitter checks the level of the data line (SDA) and compares it with the levels it expects; if they do not match, that transmitter has lost arbitration and drops out of this protocol interaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If one transmitter sets SDA to 1 (not driving a signal) and a second transmitter sets it to 0 (pull to ground), the result is that the line is low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The first transmitter then observes that the level of the line is different from that expected and concludes that another node is transmitting.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The first node to notice such a difference is the one that loses arbitration: it stops driving SDA.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If it is a controller, it also stops driving SCL and waits for a STOP; then it may try to reissue its entire message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In the meantime, the other node has not noticed any difference between the expected and actual levels on SDA and therefore continues transmission.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] It can do so without problems because so far the signal has been exactly as it expected; no other transmitter has disturbed its message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] If the two controllers are sending a message to two different targets, the one sending the lower target address always "wins" arbitration in the address stage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Since the two controllers may send messages to the same target address, and addresses sometimes refer to multiple targets, arbitration must sometimes continue into the data stages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Arbitration occurs very rarely, but is necessary for proper multi-controller support.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] As with clock stretching, not all devices support arbitration.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Those that do, generally label themselves as supporting "multi-controller" communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One case which must be handled carefully in multi-controller I2C implementations is that of the controllers talking to each other.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One controller may lose arbitration to an incoming message, and must change its role from controller to target in time to acknowledge its own address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In the extremely rare case that two controllers simultaneously send identical messages, both will regard the communication as successful, but the target will only see one message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For this reason, when a target can be accessed by multiple controllers, every command recognized by the target either must be idempotent or must be guaranteed never to be issued by two controllers at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] While I2C only arbitrates between controllers, SMBus uses arbitration in three additional contexts, where multiple targets respond to the controller, and one gets its message through.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] PMBus version 1.3 extends the SMBus alert response protocol in its "zone read" protocol.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Targets may be grouped into "zones", and all targets in a zone may be addressed to respond, with their responses masked (omitting unwanted information), inverted (so wanted information is sent as 0 bits, which win arbitration), or reordered (so the most significant information is sent first).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Arbitration ensures that the highest priority response is the one first returned to the controller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] PMBus reserves I2C addresses 0x28 and 0x37 for zone reads and writes, respectively.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] There are several possible operating modes for I2C communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] 3. because it identifies the controller (there are eight controller codes, and each controller must use a different one), it ensures that arbitration is complete before the high-speed portion of the transfer, and so the high-speed portion need not make allowances for that ability.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Some of the vendors provide a so-called non-standard *Turbo mode* with a speed up to 1.4 Mbit/s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In all modes, the clock frequency is controlled by the controller(s), and a longer-than-normal bus may be operated at a slower-than-nominal speed by underclocking.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C is popular for interfacing peripheral circuits to prototyping systems, such as the Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C does not employ a standardized connector; however, board designers have created various wiring schemes for I2C interconnections.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] To minimize the possible damage due to plugging 0.1-inch headers in backwards, some developers have suggested using alternating signal and power connections of the following wiring schemes: (GND, SCL, VCC, SDA) or (VCC, SDA, GND, SCL).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The vast majority of applications use I2C in the way it was originally designed—peripheral ICs directly wired to a processor on the same printed circuit board, and therefore over relatively short distances of less than 1 foot (30 cm), without a connector.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] However using a differential driver, an alternate version of I2C can communicate up to 20 meters (possibly over 100 meters) over CAT5 or other cable.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Several standard connectors carry I2C signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, the UEXT, the 10-pin iPack, and the 6P6C Lego Mindstorms NXT connectors carry I2C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Every HDMI and most DVI and VGA connectors carry DDC2 data over I2C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Additionally, 8P8C connectors and a CAT5 cable normally used for the Ethernet physical layer can sometimes be used to carry differential-encoded or boosted single-ended I2C signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When there are many I2C devices in a system, there can be a need to include bus buffers or multiplexers to split large bus segments into smaller ones.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This can be necessary to keep the capacitance of a bus segment below the allowable value or to allow multiple devices with the same address to be separated by a multiplexer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Many types of multiplexers and buffers exist and all must take into account the fact that I2C lines are specified to be bidirectional.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Multiplexers can be implemented with analog switches, which can tie one segment to another.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Analog switches maintain the bidirectional nature of the lines but do not isolate the capacitance of one segment from another or provide buffering capability.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Buffers can be used to isolate capacitance on one segment from another and/or allow I2C to be sent over longer cables or traces.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Buffers for bi-directional lines such as I2C must use one of several schemes for preventing latch-up.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C is open-drain, so buffers must drive a low on one side when they see a low on the other.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One method for preventing latch-up is for a buffer to have carefully selected input and output levels such that the output level of its driver is higher than its input threshold, preventing it from triggering itself.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, a buffer may have an input threshold of 0.4 V for detecting a low, but an output low level of 0.5 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This method requires that all other devices on the bus have thresholds which are compatible and often means that multiple buffers implementing this scheme cannot be put in series with one another.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Alternatively, other types of buffers exist that implement current amplifiers or keep track of the state (i.e., which side drove the bus low) to prevent latch-up.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The state method typically means that an unintended pulse is created during a hand-off when one side is driving the bus low, then the other drives it low, then the first side releases (this is common during an I2C acknowledgement).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When having a single controller, it is possible to have multiple I2C buses share the same SCL line.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The packets on each bus are either sent one after the other or at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This is possible because the communication on each bus can be subdivided into alternating short periods with high SCL followed by short periods with low SCL.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] And the clock can be stretched if one bus needs more time in one state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Advantages are using target devices with the same address at the same time and saving connections or a faster throughput by using several data lines at the same time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] These tables show the various atomic states and bit operations that may occur during an I2C message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] In addition, the remaining 112 addresses are designated for specific classes of devices, and some of them are further reserved by either related standards or common usage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] SMBus reserves some additional addresses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Although MSB `1111` is reserved for Device ID and 10-bit target (slave) addressing, it is also used by VESA DDC display dependent devices such as pointing devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] An I2C *transaction* consists of one or more *messages*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Each message begins with a start symbol, and the transaction ends with a stop symbol.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Start symbols after the first, which begin a message but not a transaction, are referred to as *repeated start* symbols.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A transaction consisting of a single message is called either a read or a write transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A transaction consisting of multiple messages is called a combined transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The most common form of the latter is a write message providing intra-device address information, followed by a read message.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Many I2C devices do not distinguish between a combined transaction and the same messages sent as separate transactions, but not all.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The device ID protocol requires a single transaction; targets are forbidden from responding if they observe a stop symbol.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Configuration, calibration or self-test modes that cause the target to respond unusually are also often automatically terminated at the end of a transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] SCL is pulled low, and SDA sets the first data bit level while keeping SCL low (during blue bar time).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The data is sampled (received) when SCL rises for the first bit (B1).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For a bit to be valid, SDA must not change between a rising edge of SCL and the subsequent falling edge (the entire green bar time).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This process repeats, SDA transitioning while SCL is low, and the data being read while SCL is high (B2 through Bn).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The final bit is followed by a clock pulse, during which SDA is pulled low in preparation for the *stop* bit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A *stop* condition (P) is signalled when SCL rises, followed by SDA rising.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] To avoid false marker detection, there is a minimum delay between the SCL falling edge and changing SDA, and between changing SDA and the SCL rising edge.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The minimum delay time is dependent upon the data transfer rate in use.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Note that an I2C message containing n data bits (including acknowledgements) contains *n* + 1 clock pulses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C lends itself to a "bus driver" software design.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Software for attached devices is written to call a "bus driver" that handles the actual low-level I2C hardware.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] This permits the driver code for attached devices to port easily to other hardware, including a bit-banging design.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When developing or troubleshooting systems using I2C, visibility at the level of hardware signals can be important.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] There are a number of I2C host adapter hardware solutions for making an I2C controller or target connection to host computers, running Linux, Mac or Windows.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Not all of them require proprietary drivers or APIs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C protocol analyzers are tools that sample an I2C bus and decode the electrical signals to provide a higher-level view of the data being transmitted on the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] When developing and/or troubleshooting the I2C bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Logic analyzers are tools that collect, analyze, decode, and store signals, so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Logic analyzers display time stamps of each signal level change, which can help find protocol problems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Most logic analyzers have the capability to decode bus signals into high-level protocol data and show ASCII data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The assignment of target addresses is a weakness of I2C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Seven bits are too few to prevent address collisions between the many thousands of available devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] What alleviates the issue of address collisions between different vendors and also allows connecting to several identical devices is that manufacturers dedicate pins that can be used to set the target address to one of a few address options per device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Two or three pins is typical, and with many devices, there are three or more wiring options per address pin.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] 10-bit I2C addresses are not yet widely used, and many host operating systems do not support them.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Neither is the complex SMBus "ARP" scheme for dynamically assigning addresses (other than for PCI cards with SMBus presence, for which it is required).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Automatic bus configuration is a related issue.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] A given address may be used by a number of different protocol-incompatible devices in various systems, and hardly any device types can be detected at runtime.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, `0x51` may be used by a 24LC02 or 24C32 EEPROM, with incompatible addressing; or by a PCF8563 RTC, which cannot reliably be distinguished from either (without changing device state, which might not be allowed).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The only reliable configuration mechanisms available to hosts involve out-of-band mechanisms such as tables provided by system firmware, which list the available devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Again, this issue can partially be addressed by ARP in SMBus systems, especially when vendor and product identifiers are used, but that has not really caught on.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] 3 version of the I2C specification adds a device ID mechanism.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Hosts supporting the multi-megabit speeds are rare.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Support for the Fm+ 1 Mbit/s speed is more widespread, since its electronics are simple variants of what is used at lower speeds.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Many devices do not support the 400 kbit/s speed (in part because SMBus does not yet support it).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] I2C nodes implemented in software (instead of dedicated hardware) may not even support the 100 kbit/s speed; so the whole range defined in the specification is rarely usable.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] All devices must at least partially support the highest speed used or they may spuriously detect their device address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Devices are allowed to stretch clock cycles to suit their particular needs, which can starve bandwidth needed by faster devices and increase latencies when talking to other device addresses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Bus capacitance also places a limit on the transfer speed, especially when current sources are not used to decrease signal rise times.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Because I2C is a shared bus, there is the potential for any device to have a fault and hang the entire bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] For example, if any device holds the SDA or SCL line low, it prevents the controller from sending START or STOP commands to reset the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Thus it is common for designs to include a reset signal that provides an external method of resetting the bus devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] However, many devices do not have a dedicated reset pin, forcing the designer to put in circuitry to allow devices to be power-cycled if they need to be reset.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Because of these limits (address management, bus configuration, potential faults, speed), few I2C bus segments have even a dozen devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Instead, it is common for systems to have several smaller segments.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] One might be dedicated to use with high-speed devices for low-latency power management.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Another might be used to control a few devices where latency and throughput are not important issues; yet another segment might be used only to read EEPROM chips describing add-on cards (such as the SPD standard used with DRAM sticks).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] On very low-power systems, the pull-up resistors can use more power than the entire rest of the design combined.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] On these, the resistors are often powered by a switchable voltage source, such as a DIO from a microcontroller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] The pull-ups also limit the speed of the bus and have a small additional cost.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p01] Therefore, some designers are turning to other serial buses that do not need pull-ups, such as I3C or SPI.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] I2C is the basis for the ACCESS.bus, the VESA Display Data Channel (DDC) interface, the System Management Bus (SMBus), Power Management Bus (PMBus) and the Intelligent Platform Management Bus (IPMB, one of the protocols of IPMI).
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] These variants have differences in voltage and clock frequency ranges, and may have interrupt lines.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] High-availability systems (AdvancedTCA, MicroTCA) use 2-way redundant I2C for shelf management.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] Multi-controller I2C capability is a requirement in these systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] TWI (Two-Wire Interface) or TWSI (Two-Wire Serial Interface) is essentially the same bus implemented on various system-on-chip processors from Atmel and other vendors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] Vendors use the name TWI, even though I2C is not a registered trademark as of 2014-11-07.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] Trademark protection only exists for the respective logo (see upper right corner), and patents on I2C have now lapsed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] According to Microchip Technology, TWI and I2C have a few differences.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] One of them is that TWI does not support START byte.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] In some cases, use of the term "two-wire interface" indicates incomplete implementation of the I2C specification.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] Not supporting arbitration or clock stretching is one common limitation, which is still useful for a single controller communicating with simple targets that never stretch the clock.
[src:hardware-interfaces/i²c-p02] MIPI I3C sensor interface standard (I3C) is a development of I2C, under development in 2017.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] JTAG implements standards for on-chip instrumentation in electronic design automation (EDA) as a complementary tool to digital simulation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] It specifies the use of a dedicated debug port implementing a serial communications interface for low-overhead access without requiring direct external access to the system address and data buses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The interface connects to an on-chip **Test Access Port** (TAP) that implements a stateful protocol to access a set of test registers that present chip logic levels and device capabilities of various parts.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group formed in 1985 to develop a method of verifying designs and testing printed circuit boards after manufacture.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In 1990, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers codified the results of the effort in IEEE Standard 1149.1-1990, entitled *Standard Test Access Port and Boundary-Scan Architecture*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The JTAG standards have been extended by multiple semiconductor chip manufacturers with specialized variants to provide vendor-specific features.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In the 1980s, multi-layer circuit boards and integrated circuits (ICs) using ball grid array and similar mounting technologies were becoming standard, and connections were being made between ICs that were not available to probes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The majority of manufacturing and field faults in circuit boards were due to poor solder joints on the boards, imperfections among board connections, or the bonds and bond wires from IC pads to pin lead frames.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) was formed in 1985 to provide a pins-out view from one IC pad to another so these faults could be discovered.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The industry standard became an IEEE standard in 1990 as IEEE Std.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In the same year, Intel released their first processor with JTAG (the 80486), which led to quicker industry adoption by all manufacturers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In 1994, a supplement that contains a description of the boundary scan description language (BSDL) was added.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Further refinements regarding the use of all-zeros for EXTEST, separating the use of SAMPLE from PRELOAD and better implementation for OBSERVE_ONLY cells were made and released in 2001.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Since 1990, this standard has been adopted by electronics companies around the world.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Boundary scan is now mostly synonymous with JTAG, but JTAG has essential uses beyond such manufacturing applications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] 1149.1 has introduced a vast set of optional features, associated extensions to BSDL, and a new procedural description language (PDL) based on Tcl.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Although JTAG's early applications targeted board-level testing, here the JTAG standard was designed to assist with device, board, and system testing, diagnosis, and fault isolation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Today JTAG is used as the primary means of accessing sub-blocks of integrated circuits, making it an essential mechanism for debugging embedded systems which might not have any other debug-capable communications channel.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] On most systems, JTAG-based debugging is available from the very first instruction after CPU reset, letting it assist with development of early boot software which runs before anything is set up.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] An in-circuit emulator (or, more correctly, a *JTAG adapter*) uses JTAG as the transport mechanism to access on-chip debug modules inside the target CPU.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Those modules let software developers debug the software of an embedded system directly at the machine instruction level when needed, or (more typically) in terms of high-level language source code.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] System software debug support is for many software developers the main reason to be interested in JTAG.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Multiple silicon architectures, such as PowerPC, MIPS, ARM, and x86, built an entire software debug, instruction tracing, and data tracing infrastructure around the basic JTAG protocol.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Frequently, individual silicon vendors, however, only implement parts of these extensions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some examples are ARM CoreSight and Nexus as well as Intel's BTS (Branch Trace Storage), LBR (Last Branch Record), and IPT (Intel Processor Trace) implementations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] There are a number of other such silicon vendor-specific extensions that may not be documented except under NDA.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The adoption of the JTAG standard helped move JTAG-centric debugging environments away from early processor-specific designs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Processors can normally be halted, single stepped, or let run freely.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] One can set code breakpoints, both for code in RAM (often using a special machine instruction e.g., INT3) and in ROM/flash.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Data breakpoints are often available, as is bulk data download to RAM.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Most designs have *halt mode debugging*, but some allow debuggers to access registers and data buses without needing to halt the core being debugged.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Sometimes FPGA developers also use JTAG to develop debugging tools.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The same JTAG techniques used to debug software running inside a CPU can help debug other digital design blocks inside an FPGA.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] For example, custom JTAG instructions can be provided to allow reading registers built from arbitrary sets of signals inside the FPGA, providing visibility for behaviors that are invisible to boundary scan operations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Similarly, writing such registers could provide controllability that is not otherwise available.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] JTAG allows device programmer hardware to transfer data into internal non-volatile device memory (e.g., CPLDs).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some device programmers serve a double purpose for programming as well as debugging the device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In the case of FPGAs, volatile memory devices can also be programmed via the JTAG port, normally during development work.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In addition, internal monitoring capabilities (temperature, voltage, and current) may be accessible via the JTAG port.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] JTAG programmers are also used to write software and data into flash memory.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is usually done using the same data bus access the CPU would use, and is sometimes handled by the CPU.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In other cases, the memory chips themselves have JTAG interfaces.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some modern debug architectures provide internal and external bus master access without needing to halt and take over a CPU.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In the worst case, it is usually possible to drive external bus signals using the boundary scan facility.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] As a practical matter, when developing an embedded system, emulating the instruction store is the fastest way to implement the *debug cycle* (edit, compile, download, test, and debug).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is because the in-circuit emulator simulating an instruction store can be updated very quickly from the development host via, say, USB.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Using a serial UART port and bootloader to upload firmware to Flash makes this debug cycle quite slow and possibly expensive in terms of tools; installing firmware into Flash (or SRAM instead of Flash) via JTAG is an intermediate solution between these extremes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] JTAG boundary scan technology provides access to a number of logic signals of a complex integrated circuit, including the device pins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The signals are represented in the boundary scan register (BSR) accessible via the TAP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This permits testing as well as controlling the states of the signals for testing and debugging.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Therefore, both software and hardware (manufacturing) faults may be located and an operating device may be monitored.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] When combined with built-in self-test (BIST), the JTAG scan chain enables a low-overhead embedded solution to test an IC for certain static faults (shorts, opens, and logic errors).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The scan chain mechanism does not generally help diagnose or test for timing, temperature or other dynamic operational errors that may occur.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Test cases are often provided in standardized formats such as SVF, or its binary sibling XSVF, and used in production tests.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The ability to perform such testing on finished boards is an essential part of Design For Test in today's products, increasing the number of faults that can be found before products ship to customers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A JTAG interface is a special interface added to a chip.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Depending on the version of JTAG, two, four, or five pins are added.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The four and five-pin interfaces are designed so that multiple chips on a board can have their JTAG lines daisy-chained together if specific conditions are met.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The two-pin interface is designed so that multiple chips can be connected in a star topology.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In either case, a test probe needs only connect to a single JTAG port to have access to all chips on a circuit board.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The TRST pin is an optional active-low reset to the test logic, usually asynchronous, but sometimes synchronous, depending on the chip.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] If the pin is not available, the test logic can be reset by switching to the reset state synchronously, using TCK and TMS.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Note that resetting test logic doesn't necessarily imply resetting anything else.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] There are generally some processor-specific JTAG operations that can reset all or part of the chip being debugged.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Since only one data line is available, the protocol is serial.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] One bit of data is transferred in from TDI and out to TDO per TCK rising clock edge.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Instructions for typical ICs might read the chip ID, sample input pins, drive (or float) output pins, manipulate chip functions, or bypass (pipe TDI to TDO to logically shorten chains of multiple chips).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] As with any clocked signal, data presented to TDI must be valid for some chip-specific *Setup* time before and *Hold* time after the relevant (here, rising) clock edge.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] TDO data is valid for some chip-specific time after the falling edge of TCK.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The maximum operating frequency of TCK varies depending on all chips in the chain (the lowest speed must be used), but it is typically 10-100 MHz (100-10 ns per bit).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Also, TCK frequencies depend on board layout and JTAG adapter capabilities and state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] One chip might have a 40 MHz JTAG clock, but only if it is using a 200 MHz clock for non-JTAG operations; and it might need to use a much slower clock when it is in a low-power mode.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Accordingly, some JTAG adapters have *adaptive clocking* using an RTCK (Return TCK) signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Faster TCK frequencies are most useful when JTAG is used to transfer large amounts of data, such as when storing a program executable into flash memory.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Clocking changes on TMS steps through a standardized JTAG state machine.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The JTAG state machine can reset, access an instruction register, or access data selected by the instruction register.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] JTAG platforms often add signals to the handful defined by the IEEE 1149.1 specification.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A System Reset (SRST) signal is quite common, letting debuggers reset the whole system, not just the parts with JTAG support.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Sometimes, there are event signals used to trigger activity by the host or by the device being monitored through JTAG, or, perhaps, additional control lines.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Even though few consumer products provide an explicit JTAG port connector, the connections are often available on the printed circuit board as a remnant from development prototyping and/or production.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] When exploited, these connections often provide the most viable means for reverse engineering.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Reduced pin count JTAG uses only two wires, a clock wire and a data wire.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is defined as part of the IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The two-wire interface reduced pressure on the number of pins, and devices can be connected in a star topology.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The star topology enables some parts of the system to be powered down, while others can still be accessed over JTAG; a daisy chain requires all JTAG interfaces to be powered.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Other two-wire interfaces exist, such as Serial Wire Debug (SWD) and Spy-Bi-Wire (SBW).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In JTAG, devices expose one or more *test access ports* (TAPs).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The picture above shows three TAPs, which might be individual chips or might be modules inside one chip.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A daisy chain of TAPs is called a *scan chain*, or (loosely) a target.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Scan chains can be arbitrarily long, but in practice, twenty TAPs is unusually long.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] To use JTAG, a host is connected to the target's JTAG signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO, etc.) through some kind of *JTAG adapter*, which may need to handle issues like level shifting and galvanic isolation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The adapter connects to the host using some interface such as USB, PCI, Ethernet, and so forth.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The host communicates with the TAPs by manipulating TMS and TDI in conjunction with TCK and reading results through TDO (which is the only standard host-side input).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] At a basic level, using JTAG involves reading and writing instructions and their associated data registers, and sometimes involves running a number of test cycles.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Behind those registers is hardware that is not specified by JTAG, and which has its own states that are affected by JTAG activities.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Most JTAG hosts use the shortest path between two states, perhaps constrained by quirks of the adapter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] (For example, one adapter only handles paths whose lengths are multiples of seven bits.) Some layers built on top of JTAG monitor the state transitions and use uncommon paths to trigger higher-level operations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some ARM cores use such sequences to enter and exit a two-wire (non-JTAG) SWD mode.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A Zero Bit Scan (ZBS) sequence is used in IEEE 1149.7 to access advanced functionality such as switching TAPs into and out of scan chains, power management, and a different two-wire mode.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Instruction register sizes tend to be small, perhaps four or seven bits wide.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Except for BYPASS and EXTEST, all instruction opcodes are defined by the TAP implementer, as are their associated data registers; undefined instruction codes should not be used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] On exit from the RESET state, the instruction register is preloaded with either BYPASS or IDCODE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This allows JTAG hosts to identify the size and, at least partially, contents of the scan chain to which they are connected.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] (They can enter the RESET state, then scan the Data Register until they read back the data they wrote.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A BYPASS register has only a zero bit, while an IDCODE register is 32 bits and starts with a one.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] So the bits not written by the host can easily be mapped to TAPs.) Such identification is often used to sanity-check manual configuration since IDCODE is often nonspecific.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] It could, for example, identify an ARM Cortex-M3-based microcontroller, without specifying the microcontroller vendor or model; or a particular FPGA, but not how it has been programmed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A common idiom involves shifting BYPASS into the instruction registers of all TAPs except one, which receives some other instruction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] That way, all TAPs except one expose a single-bit data register, and values can be selectively shifted into or out of that one TAP's data register without affecting any other TAP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The IEEE 1149.1 (JTAG) standard describes a number of instructions to support boundary scan applications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some of these instructions are *mandatory*, but TAPs used for debug instead of boundary scan testing sometimes provide minimal or no support for these instructions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Devices may define more instructions, and those definitions should be part of a BSDL file provided by the manufacturer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Devices communicate to the world via a set of input and output pins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] By themselves, these pins provide limited visibility into the workings of the device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] However, devices that support boundary scan contain a shift-register cell for each signal pin of the device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] These registers are connected in a dedicated path around the device's boundary (hence the name).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The path creates a virtual access capability that circumvents the normal inputs and outputs, providing direct control of the device and detailed visibility for signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The contents of the boundary scan register, including signal I/O capabilities, are usually described by the manufacturer using a part-specific BSDL file.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] These are used with design 'netlists' from CAD/EDA systems to develop tests used in board manufacturing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Commercial test systems often cost several thousand dollars for a complete system and include diagnostic options to pinpoint faults such as open circuits and shorts.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] They may also offer schematic or layout viewers to depict the fault in a graphical manner.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] To enable boundary scanning, IC vendors add logic to each of their devices, including scan cells for each of the signal pins.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] These cells are then connected together to form the boundary scan shift register (BSR), which is connected to a TAP controller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] These designs are parts of most Verilog or VHDL libraries.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Overhead for this additional logic is minimal, and generally is well worth the price to enable efficient testing at the board level.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] An example helps show the operation of JTAG in real systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The example here is the debug TAP of an ARM11 processor, the ARM1136 core.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The processor itself has extensive JTAG capability, similar to what is found in other CPU cores, and it is integrated into chips with even more extensive capabilities accessed through JTAG.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is a non-trivial example, which is representative of a significant cross section of JTAG-enabled systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In addition, it shows how control mechanisms are built using JTAG's register read/write primitives, and how those combine to facilitate testing and debugging complex logic elements; CPUs are common, but FPGAs and ASICs include other complex elements which need to be debugged.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Licensees of this core integrate it into chips, usually combining it with other TAPs as well as numerous peripherals and memory.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] One of those other TAPs handles boundary scan testing for the whole chip; it is not supported by the debug TAP.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] That scan chain modification is one subject of a forthcoming IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] That model resembles the model used in other ARM cores.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Non-ARM systems generally have similar capabilities, perhaps implemented using the Nexus protocols on top of JTAG, or other vendor-specific schemes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Older ARM7 and ARM9 cores include an *EmbeddedICE* module which combines most of those facilities, but has an awkward mechanism for instruction execution: the debugger must drive the CPU instruction pipeline, clock by clock, and directly access the data buses to read and write data to the CPU.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The ARM11 uses the same model for trace support (ETM, ETB) as those older cores.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Newer ARM Cortex cores closely resemble this debug model, but build on a *Debug Access Port* (DAP) instead of direct CPU access.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In this architecture (named *CoreSight Technology*), core and JTAG module is completely independent.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] They are also decoupled from JTAG so they can be hosted over ARM's two-wire **SWD** interface (see below) instead of just the six-wire JTAG interface.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] (ARM takes the four standard JTAG signals and adds the optional TRST, plus the RTCK signal used for adaptive clocking.) The CoreSight JTAG-DP is asynchronous to the core clocks, and does not implement RTCK.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Also, the newer cores have updated trace support.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] One basic way to debug software is to present a single-threaded model, where the debugger periodically stops execution of the program and examines its state as exposed by register contents and memory (including peripheral controller registers).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] When interesting program events approach, a person may want to single-step instructions (or lines of source code) to watch how a particular misbehavior happens.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] So, for example, a JTAG host might HALT the core, entering debug mode, and then read CPU registers using ITR and DCC.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] After saving processor state, it could write those registers with whatever values it needs, then execute arbitrary algorithms on the CPU, accessing memory and peripherals to help characterize the system state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] After the debugger performs those operations, the state may be restored and execution continued using the RESTART instruction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Debug mode is also entered asynchronously by the debug module, triggering a watchpoint or breakpoint, or by issuing a BKPT (breakpoint) instruction from the software being debugged.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] When it is not being used for instruction tracing, the ETM can also trigger entry to debug mode; it supports complex triggers sensitive to state and history, as well as the simple address comparisons exposed by the debug module.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Asynchronous transitions to debug mode are detected by polling the DSCR register.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is how single stepping is implemented: HALT the core, set a temporary breakpoint at the next instruction or next high-level statement, RESTART, poll DSCR until you detect asynchronous entry to debug state, remove that temporary breakpoint, repeat.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Modern software is often too complex to work well with such a single-threaded model.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] For example, a processor used to control a motor (perhaps one driving a saw blade) may not be able to safely enter halt mode; it may need to continue handling interrupts to ensure physical safety of people and/or machinery.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Issuing a HALT instruction using JTAG might be dangerous.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] ARM processors support an alternative debug mode, called *Monitor Mode*, to work with such situations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This monitor communicates with the debugger using the DCC and could arrange, for example, to single step only a single process while other processes (and interrupt handlers) continue running.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Microprocessor vendors have often defined their own core-specific debugging extensions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Such vendors include Infineon, MIPS with EJTAG, and more.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] If the vendor does not adopt a standard (such as the ones used by ARM processors or Nexus), they need to define their own solution.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] If they support boundary scan, they generally build debugging over JTAG.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Freescale has COP and OnCE (On-Chip Emulation).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] OnCE includes a JTAG command which makes a TAP enter a special mode where the IR holds OnCE debugging commands for operations such as single stepping, breakpointing, and accessing registers or memory.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] It also defines EOnCE (Enhanced On-Chip Emulation) presented as addressing real-time concerns.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Note that tracing is non-invasive; systems do not need to stop operating to be traced.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Nexus defines a processor debug infrastructure that is largely vendor-independent.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] It also defines a high-speed auxiliary port interface, used for tracing and more.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Nexus is used with some newer platforms, such as the Atmel AVR32 and Freescale MPC5500 series processors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The target's JTAG interface is accessed using some JTAG-enabled application and some JTAG adapter hardware.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] There is a wide range of such hardware, optimized for purposes such as production testing, debugging high-speed systems, low-cost microcontroller development, and so on.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] In the same way, the software used to drive such hardware can be quite varied.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Software developers mostly use JTAG for debugging and updating firmware.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] There are no official standards for JTAG adapter physical connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Development boards usually include a header to support preferred development tools; in some cases, they include multiple such headers because they need to support multiple such tools.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] For example, a microcontroller, FPGA, and ARM application processor rarely share tools, so a development board using all of those components might have three or more headers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Production boards may omit the headers, or when space is limited, may provide JTAG signal access using test points.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Those connectors tend to include more than just the four standardized signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Usually, reset signals are provided, one or both of TRST (TAP reset) and SRST (system reset).
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The connector usually provides the board-under-test's logic supply voltage so that the JTAG adapters use the appropriate logic levels.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The board voltage may also serve as a *board present* debugger input.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Other event input or output signals may be provided, or general purpose I/O (GPIO) lines, to support more complex debugging architectures.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Higher end products frequently use dense connectors (frequently 38-pin MICTOR connectors) to support high-speed tracing in conjunction with JTAG operations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] A recent trend is to have development boards integrate a USB interface to JTAG, where a second channel is used for a serial port.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] (Smaller boards can also be powered through USB.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Since modern PCs tend to omit serial ports, such integrated debug links can significantly reduce clutter for developers.) Production boards often rely on bed-of-nails connections to test points for testing and programming.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] There are both *dumb* adapters, where the host decides and performs all JTAG operations; and *smart* ones, where some of that work is performed inside the adapter, often driven by a microcontroller.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] The *smart* adapters eliminate link latencies for operation sequences that may involve polling for status changes between steps, and may accordingly offer higher throughput.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] As of 2018, adapters with a USB link from the host are the most common approach.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Higher-end products often support Ethernet, with the advantage that the debug host can be quite remote.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Adapters that support high-speed trace ports generally include several megabytes of trace buffer and provide high-speed links (USB or Ethernet) to get that data to the host.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Parallel port adapters are simple and inexpensive, but they are relatively slow because they use the host CPU to change each bit ("bit banging").
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] They have declined in usefulness because most computers in recent years don't have a parallel port.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Driver support is also a problem because pin usage by adapters varies widely.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Since the parallel port is based on 5 V logic level, most adapters lacked voltage translation support for 3.3 V or 1.8 V target voltages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] RS-232 serial port adapters also exist and are similarly declining in usefulness.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] They generally involve either slower bit banging than a parallel port or a microcontroller translating some command protocol to JTAG operations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Such serial adapters are also not fast, but their command protocols could generally be reused on top of higher-speed links.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] With all JTAG adapters, software support is a basic concern.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Some vendors do not publish the protocols used by their JTAG adapter hardware, limiting their customers to the tool chains supported by those vendors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] This is a particular issue for "smart" adapters, some of which embed significant amounts of knowledge about how to interact with specific CPUs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Most development environments for embedded software include JTAG support.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] All such software tends to include basic debugger support: stopping, halting, single stepping, breakpoints, data structure browsing, and so on.
[src:hardware-interfaces/jtag] Commercial tools tend to provide tools like very accurate simulators and trace analysis, which are not currently available as open source.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus is popular in industrial environments because it is openly published and royalty-free.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] It was developed for industrial applications, is relatively easy to deploy and maintain compared to other standards, and places few restrictions on the format of the data to be transmitted.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The Modbus protocol uses serial communication lines, Ethernet, or the Internet protocol suite as a transport layer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus supports communication to and from multiple devices connected to the same cable or Ethernet network.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For example, there can be a device that measures temperature and another device to measure humidity connected to the same cable, both communicating measurements to the same computer, via Modbus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus is often used to connect a plant/system supervisory computer with a remote terminal unit (RTU) in supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Many of the data types are named from industrial control of factory devices, such as ladder logic because of its use in driving relays: a single-bit physical output is called a *coil*, and a single-bit physical input is called a *discrete input* or a *contact*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] It was originally published in 1979 by Modicon (bought by Schneider Electric in 1997).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In 2004, they transferred the rights to the Modbus Organization which is a trade association of users and suppliers of Modbus-compliant devices that advocates for the continued use of the technology.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] To support Modbus communication on a network, many modems and gateways incorporate proprietary designs (refer to the diagram: *Architecture of a network for Modbus communication*).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Implementations may deploy either wireline or wireless communication, such as in the ISM radio band, and even Short Message Service (SMS) or General Packet Radio Service (GPRS).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus defines a *client* which is an entity that initiates a transaction to request any specific task from its *request receiver*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The client's "request receiver", which the client has initiated the transaction with, is then called the *server*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For example, when a microcontroller connects to a sensor to read its data by Modbus on a wired network, e.g RS485 bus, the MCU in this context is the client and the sensor is the server.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In former terminology, the client was named master and the server named slave.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus defines a protocol data unit (PDU) independently to its lower layer protocols in its protocol stack.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Mapping MODBUS protocol on specific buses or networks requires some additional fields, defined as the application data unit (ADU).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The ADU is formed by a *client* inside a Modbus network when the client initiates a transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The ADU is officially called a *Modbus frame* by the Modbus Organization, although *frame* is used as the data unit in the data-link layer in the OSI and TCP/IP model (while Modbus is an application layer protocol).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] ADU max size on RS232/RS485 network is 256 bytes, and with TCP is 260 bytes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For data encoding, Modbus uses a big-endian representation for addresses and data fields.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Thus, for a 16-bit value, the most significant byte is sent first.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For example, when a 16-bit register has value 0x1234, byte 0x12 is sent before byte 0x34.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The data field of the PDU has the address from 0 to 65535 (not to be confused with the address of the Additional address field of ADU).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The data field of the PDU can be empty, and then has a size of 0.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In this case, the server will not request any information and the function code defines the function to be executed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] If there is no error during the execution process, the data field of the ADU response from server to client will include the data requested, i.e. the data the client previously received.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] If there is any error, the server will respond with an exception code.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] field's size depends on the function code and usually includes values like variable values, data offset, and sub-function codes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] is equal to the Function code, except that its MSB is set to 1.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For each of the primary tables, the protocol allows individual selection of 65536 data items, and the operations of read or write of those items are designed to span multiple consecutive data items up to a data size limit which is dependent on the transaction function code.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus defines three types of function codes: Public, User-Defined and Reserved.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Note: Some sources use terminology that differs from the standard; for example *Force Single Coil* instead of *Write Single Coil*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] On a successful execution, mb_rsp_pdu will return one byte to note the function code (0x01), followed by one byte to indicate the number of data bytes it is returning (n), which will be the number of coils requested by mb_req_pdu, divided by 8 bits per byte, and rounded up.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The remainder of the response will be the specified number (n) of data bytes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Starting Address (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which is the 20th coil.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Quantity of Outputs (2 bytes) is 0x0013, (or 19 in decimal) which corresponds to 19 values of status of coils 20th to 38th.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] As 19 coils (20-38) are required, 3 bytes is used to indicate the coil's state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] States of coil from 20 to 27 is 0xCD, which is 1100 1101 in binary.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] With coil from 36 to 38, the state will be 0x05, which is 0000 0101.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Coil 38 state is the 3rd bit (count from the right), i.e 1, coil 37 is 0, and coil 36 state is LSb bit, i.e.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] User-Defined Function Codes are function codes defined by users.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus gives two range of values for user-defined function codes: 65 to 72 and 100 to 110.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Obviously, user-defined function codes are not unique.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Reserved Function Codes are function codes used by some companies for legacy product and are not available for public use.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus standard also defines Modbus over Serial Line, a protocol over the data link layer of the OSI model for the Modbus application layer protocol to be communicated over a serial bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus Serial Line protocol is a master-slave protocol which supports one master and multiple slaves in the serial bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] With Modbus protocol on the application layer, client/server model is used for the devices on the communication channel.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] With Modbus over Serial Line, *client*'s role is implemented by *master*, and the *server*'s role is implemented by *slave*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The organization's naming convention inverts the common usage of having multiple clients and only one server.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] To avoid this confusion, the RS-485 transport layer uses the terms "node" or "device" instead of "server", and the "client" is not a "node".
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] A serial bus for Modbus over Serial Line can have a maximum of 247 slaves communicating with one master.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Those slaves have a unique address ranging from 1 to 247 (01hex to F7hex).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The addresses from 248 to 255 (F8hex … FFhex) are reserved and must not be used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The master doesn't need to have an address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The communication process is initiated by the master, as only it can initiate a Modbus transaction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] A slave will never transmit any data or perform any action without a request from the master, and slaves cannot communicate with each other.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In Modbus over Serial Line, the master initiates requests to the slaves in *unicast* or *broadcast* modes.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In *unicast mode*, the master will initiate a request to a single slave with a specific address.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Upon receiving and finishing the request, the slave will respond with a message to the master.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In this mode, a Modbus transaction includes two messages: one request from the master and one reply from the slave.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Each slave must have a unique address (from 1 to 247) to be addressed independently for the communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] In *broadcast mode*, the master can send a request to all the slaves, using the broadcast address 0, which is the address reserved for broadcast exchanges (and not the master address).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Slaves must accept broadcast exchanges but must not respond.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The mapping of PDU of Modbus to the serial bus of Modbus over Serial Line protocol results in Modbus Serial Line PDU.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] On the physical layer, MODBUS over Serial Line performs its communication on bit by RS485 or RS232, with TIA/EIA-485 Two-Wire interface as the most popular way.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] TIA/EIA-232-E (RS232) can also be used but is limited to point-to-point short-range communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] MODBUS over Serial Line has two transmission modes *RTU* and *ASCII* which are corresponded to two versions of the protocol, known as *Modbus RTU* and *Modbus ASCII*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus RTU (Remote Terminal Unit), which is the most common implementation available for Modbus, makes use of a compact, binary representation of the data for protocol communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The RTU format follows the commands/data with a cyclic redundancy check checksum as an error check mechanism to ensure the reliability of data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] A Modbus RTU message must be transmitted continuously without inter-character hesitations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus messages are framed (separated) by idle (silent) periods.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The default is even parity, while odd or no parity may be implemented as additional options.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The CRC calculation is widely known as CRC-16-MODBUS, whose polynomial is *x*16 + *x*15 + *x*2 + 1 (normal hexadecimal algebraic polynomial being `8005` and reversed `A001`).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Example of a Modbus RTU frame in hexadecimal: `01 04 02 FF FF B8 80` (CRC-16-MODBUS calculation for the 5 bytes from `01` to `FF` gives `80B8`, which is transmitted least significant byte first).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] To ensure frame integrity during the transmission, the time interval between two frames must be at least the transmission time of 3.5 characters, and the time interval between two consecutive characters must be no more than the transmission time of 1.5 characters.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For higher data rates, Modbus RTU recommends to use the fixed values 750 μs for t1.5 and 1.750 ms for t3.5.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus ASCII makes use of ASCII characters (chars) for protocol communication.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The ASCII format uses a longitudinal redundancy check checksum.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus ASCII messages are framed by a leading colon (":", ASCII value 3A16) and trailing newline (CR/LF, ASCII values 0D16 and 0A16).
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus ASCII frame do not need to be sent in bursts like Modbus RTU, a delay up to 1 second is permitted between each character transmission by default.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Address, Function, Data, and LRC are ASCII hexadecimal encoded values, whereby each byte (8 bits) of information is encoded as two human-readable ASCII characters from the ranges 0–9 and A–F.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] For example, a byte value of 122 (11110102 or 7A16) is encoded as two ASCII characters, "7" and "A", and transmitted as two bytes, `55` (3716, ASCII value for "7") and `65` (4116, ASCII value for "A").
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] LRC is calculated as the sum of 8-bit values (excluding the start and end characters), negated (two's complement) and encoded as an 8-bit value.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] LRC is specified for use only as a checksum: because it is calculated on the encoded data rather than the transmitted characters, its 'longitudinal' characteristic is not available for use with parity bits to locate single-bit errors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Modbus TCP nomenclature is the same as for the Modbus over Serial line protocol, as any device which send out a Modbus command, is the 'client' and the response comes from a 'server'.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] The ADU for Modbus TCP is officially called *Modbus TCP/IP ADU* by the Modbus organization and is also called *Modbus TCP frame* by other parties.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] MODBUS Application Protocol header - is the dedicated header used on TCP/IP to identify the MODBUS Application Data Unit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Data models and function calls are identical for the first four variants listed above; only the encapsulation is different.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] However the variants are not interoperable, nor are the frame formats.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Another *de facto* protocol closely related to Modbus appeared later, and was defined by PLC maker April Automates, the result of a collaborative effort between French companies Renault Automation and Merlin Gerin et Cie in 1985: JBUS.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] Differences between Modbus and JBUS at that time (number of entities, server stations) are now irrelevant as this protocol almost disappeared with the April PLC series, which AEG Schneider Automation bought in 1994 and then made obsolete.
[src:hardware-interfaces/modbus] However, the name JBUS has survived to some extent.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is useful for controlling the average power or amplitude delivered by an electrical signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The average value of voltage (and current) fed to the load is controlled by switching the supply between 0 and 100% at a rate faster than it takes the load to change significantly.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The longer the switch is on, the higher the total power supplied to the load.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Along with maximum power point tracking (MPPT), it is one of the primary methods of controlling the output of solar panels to that which can be utilized by a battery.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is particularly suited for running inertial loads such as motors, which are not as easily affected by this discrete switching.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The goal of PWM is to control a load; however, the PWM switching frequency must be selected carefully in order to smoothly do so.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM switching frequency can vary greatly depending on load and application.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Choosing a switching frequency that is too high for the application may cause premature failure of mechanical control components, despite getting smooth control of the load.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Selecting a switching frequency that is too low for the application causes oscillations in the load.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The main advantage of PWM is that power loss in the switching devices is very low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When a switch is off, there is practically no current, and when it is on and power is being transferred to the load, there is almost no voltage drop across the switch.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Power loss, being the product of voltage and current, is thus in both cases close to zero.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM also works well with digital controls, which, because of their on/off nature, can easily set the needed duty cycle.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM has also been used in certain communication systems where its duty cycle has been used to convey information over a communications channel.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The term *duty cycle* describes the proportion of 'on' time to the regular interval or 'period' of time; a low duty cycle corresponds to low power, because the power is off for most of the time.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Duty cycle is expressed in percent, 100% being fully on.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal is on half of the time and off the other half of the time, the digital signal has a duty cycle of 50% and resembles a "square" wave.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the on state than the off state, it has a duty cycle of >50%.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When a digital signal spends more time in the off state than the on state, it has a duty cycle of <50%.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The Corliss steam engine was patented in 1849.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] It used pulse-width modulation to control the intake valve of a steam engine cylinder.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] A centrifugal governor was used to provide automatic feedback.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Some machines (such as a sewing machine motor) require partial or variable power.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In the past, control (such as in a sewing machine's foot pedal) was implemented by use of a rheostat connected in series with the motor to adjust the amount of current flowing through the motor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] It was an inefficient scheme, as this also wasted power as heat in the resistor element of the rheostat, but tolerable because the total power was low.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] While the rheostat was one of several methods of controlling power (see autotransformers and Variac for more info), a low-cost and efficient power switching and adjustment method was yet to be found.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This mechanism also needed to be able to drive motors for fans, pumps and robotic servomechanisms, and needed to be compact enough to interface with lamp dimmers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM emerged as a solution for this complex problem.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM telecommunications systems were invented just prior to the start of World War II, but at that time time-division multiplexing was already in use and there were only experimental PWM systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This changed with the introduction of the cavity magnetron in 1940, which could produce pulses of microwave frequency energy but could not vary its frequency or precisely control its amplitude.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] A PWM encoder was used to trigger a magnetron in the British Army's Wireless Set Number 10, which provided long-distance telephone relay, up to 80 kilometres (50 mi).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] V. company had designed an optical scanning system for variable area film soundtrack which used PWM while it was scanning the optical audio track transversely with a thin light beam.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The electronics then evaluated the threshold between exposed (non-translucent) and unexposed (translucent) parts of the audio track.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The proposed system was to reduce noise when playing a film soundtrack.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] One early application of PWM was in the Sinclair X10, a 10 W audio amplifier available in kit form in the 1960s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] At around the same time, PWM started to be used in AC motor control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In the mid-1970s, early automotive applications of pulse-width modulation (PWM) were developed in the UK by Associated Engineering Developments Ltd (AED).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Engineers Norman Hunt and John Noddings designed systems that used pulse-width modulated electrical signals to control high-speed solenoid valves.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] By altering the signal's duty cycle, the system could vary hydraulic and pneumatic pressure instead of just turning a solenoid valve fully open or fully closed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This technology was commercialised through AED's subsidiary company, Econocruise Ltd, based in Rugby, Warwickshire.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The company used these modulated solenoid valves in pneumatic assemblies to control throttle actuators, supplying cruise control systems for luxury passenger cars and PWM speed limiters for heavy commercial trucks and buses.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This latter expression can be fairly simplified in many cases where $y_{\text{min}}=0$ as ${\bar {y}}=D\cdot y_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] From this, the average value of the signal ( ${\bar {y}}$ ) is directly dependent on the duty cycle D.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] However, by varying (i.e. modulating) the duty cycle (and possibly also the period), the following more advanced pulse-width modulated waves allow variation of the average value of the waveform.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The intersective method is a simple way to generate a PWM output signal (magenta in above figure) with fixed period and varying duty cycle is by using a comparator to switch the PWM output state when the input waveform (red) intersects with a sawtooth or a triangle waveform (blue).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Many digital circuits can generate PWM signals (e.g., many microcontrollers have PWM outputs).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] They normally use a counter that increments periodically (it is connected directly or indirectly to the clock of the circuit) and is reset at the end of every period of the PWM.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When the counter value is more than the reference value, the PWM output changes state from high to low (or low to high).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This technique is referred to as **time proportioning,** particularly as **time-proportioning control** – which *proportion* of a fixed cycle time is spent in the high state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The incremented and periodically reset counter is the discrete version of the intersecting method's sawtooth.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The analog comparator of the intersecting method becomes a simple integer comparison between the current counter value and the digital (possibly digitized) reference value.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The duty cycle can only be varied in discrete steps, as a function of the counter resolution.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] However, a high-resolution counter can provide quite satisfactory performance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The resulting spectra (of the three alignments) are similar.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Each contains a DC component, a base sideband containing the modulating signal, and phase modulated carriers at each harmonic of the frequency of the pulse.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The amplitudes of the harmonic groups are restricted by a $\sin x/x$ envelope (sinc function) and extend to infinity.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The infinite bandwidth is caused by the nonlinear operation of the pulse-width modulator.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In consequence, a digital PWM suffers from aliasing distortion that significantly reduce its applicability for modern communication systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] By limiting the bandwidth of the PWM kernel, aliasing effects can be avoided.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] On the contrary, delta modulation and delta-sigma modulation are random processes that produces a continuous spectrum without distinct harmonics.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] While intersective PWM uses a fixed period but a varying duty cycle, the period of delta and delta-sigma modulated PWMs varies in addition to their duty cycle.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Delta modulation produces a PWM signal (magenta in the above figure) which changes state whenever its integral (blue) hits the limits (green) surrounding the input (red).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Asynchronous (i.e., unclocked) delta-sigma modulation produces a PWM output (blue in bottom plot) which is subtracted from the input signal (green in top plot) to form an error signal (blue in top plot).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This error is integrated (magenta in the middle plot).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When the integral of the error exceeds the limits (the upper and lower grey lines in the middle plot), the PWM output changes state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] By integrating the difference of the error with the input signal, delta-sigma modulation shapes noise of the resulting spectrum is more concentrated in higher frequencies above the input signal's band.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Direct torque control is a method used to control AC motors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] It is closely related to the delta modulation (see above).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Motor torque and magnetic flux are estimated and these are controlled to stay within their hysteresis bands by turning on a new combination of the device's semiconductor switches each time either signal tries to deviate out of its band.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The process of PWM conversion is non-linear, and it is generally supposed that low-pass filter signal recovery is imperfect for PWM.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In electronics, many modern microcontrollers (MCUs) integrate **PWM controllers** exposed to external pins as peripheral devices under firmware control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] These are commonly used for direct current (DC) motor control in robotics, switched-mode power supply regulation, and other applications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The type of PWM controller found in MCUs is based on a digital counter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In the basic output mode, the counter is compared against a threshold level to determine whether a signal should be output.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] As a result, the threshold level determines the duty cycle.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] (This is a digital version of the intersective method from above.) Some PWMs include a way to control the period/frequency, either a configurable clock divider or a "prescaling" counter.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Many PWM controllers are also input devices: they can measure the characteristics (frequency, duty cycle) of an input PWM signal using their inbuilt counters and triggers that fire at the falling or rising edge of the input signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Using two edges of the same type produces the frequency/period; using two edge measurements of different types produces the "on" or "off"-duration, which when divided by period produces the duty cycle.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is used to control servomechanisms; see servo control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The PWM output of a microcontroller is almost never used to directly drive a motor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Instead, this signal is interpreted by a motor controller, which converts it into a more accurate PWM signal for the motor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of "PWM controller" used in robotics is derived from PWM controllers used in hobby radio control vehicles.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In telecommunications, PWM is a form of signal modulation where the widths of the pulses correspond to specific data values encoded at one end and decoded at the other.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Pulses of various lengths (the information itself) will be sent at regular intervals (the carrier frequency of the modulation).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The inclusion of a clock signal is not necessary, as the leading edge of the data signal can be used as the clock if a small offset is added to each data value to avoid a data value with a zero length pulse.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM can be used to control the amount of power delivered to a load without incurring the losses that would result from linear power delivery by resistive means.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Drawbacks to this technique are that the power drawn by the load is not constant but rather discontinuous (see Buck converter), and energy delivered to the load is not continuous either.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] However, the load may be inductive, and with a sufficiently high frequency and when necessary using additional passive electronic filters, the pulse train can be smoothed and an average analog waveform recovered.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow into the load can be continuous.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Power flow from the supply is not constant and will require energy storage on the supply side in most cases.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] High frequency PWM power control systems are easily realisable with semiconductor switches.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] As explained above, almost no power is dissipated by the switch in either on or off state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] However, during the transitions between on and off states, both voltage and current are nonzero and thus power is dissipated in the switches.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] By quickly changing the state between fully on and fully off (typically less than 100 nanoseconds), the power dissipation in the switches can be quite low compared to the power being delivered to the load.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Modern semiconductor switches such as MOSFETs or insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs) are well-suited components for high-efficiency controllers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Frequency converters used to control AC motors may have efficiencies exceeding 98%.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Switching power supplies have lower efficiency due to low output voltage levels (often even less than 2 V for microprocessors are needed), but still more than 70–80% efficiency can be achieved.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Variable-speed computer fan controllers usually use PWM, as it is far more efficient when compared to a potentiometer or rheostat.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Light dimmers for home use employ a specific type of PWM control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Home-use light dimmers typically include electronic circuitry that suppresses current flow during defined portions of each cycle of the AC line voltage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Adjusting the brightness of light emitted by a light source is then merely a matter of setting at what voltage (or phase) in the AC half-cycle the dimmer begins to provide electric current to the light source (e.g. by using an electronic switch such as a triac).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In this case the PWM duty cycle is the ratio of the conduction time to the duration of the half AC cycle defined by the frequency of the AC line voltage (50 or 60 Hz, depending on the country).
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Some other types of light sources, such as light-emitting diodes (LEDs), however, turn on and off extremely rapidly and would perceivably flicker if supplied with low-frequency drive voltages.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Perceivable flicker effects from such rapid-response light sources can be reduced by increasing the PWM frequency.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] If the light fluctuations are sufficiently rapid (faster than the flicker fusion threshold), the human visual system can no longer resolve them, and the eye perceives the time average intensity without flicker.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] In electric cookers, continuously variable power is applied to the heating elements, such as the hob or the grill, using a device known as a simmerstat.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This consists of a thermal oscillator running at approximately two cycles per minute, and the mechanism varies the duty cycle according to the knob setting.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The thermal time constant of the heating elements is several minutes, so that the temperature fluctuations are too small to matter in practice.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM is also used in efficient voltage regulators.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] By switching the voltage to the load with the appropriate duty cycle, the output will approximate a voltage at the desired level.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The switching noise is usually filtered with an inductor and a capacitor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When it is lower than the desired voltage, it turns on the switch.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] When the output voltage is above the desired voltage, it turns off the switch.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] PWM techniques would typically be used to make some indicator (like an LED) *soft blink*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The light will slowly go from dark to full intensity, and then slowly dim to dark again.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The period would be several soft blinks per second, up to several seconds for one blink.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] An indicator of this type would not disturb as much as a *hard-blinking* on/off indicator.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The indicator lamp on the Apple iBook G4, PowerBook 6,7 (2005) was of this type.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This kind of indicator is also called *pulsing glow*, as opposed to calling it *flashing*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Varying the duty cycle of a pulse waveform in a synthesis instrument creates useful timbral variations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Some synthesizers have a duty-cycle trimmer for their square-wave outputs, and that trimmer can be set by ear; the 50% point (true square wave) is distinctive because even-numbered harmonics essentially disappear at 50%.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Pulse waves, usually 50%, 25%, and 12.5%, make up the soundtracks of classic video games.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The term PWM as used in sound (music) synthesis, refers to the ratio between the high and low levels being secondarily modulated with a low-frequency oscillator.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This gives a sound effect similar to chorus or slightly detuned oscillators played together.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Class-D amplifiers produce a PWM equivalent of a lower frequency input signal that can be sent to a loudspeaker via a suitable filter network to block the carrier and recover the original lower frequency signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Since they switch power directly from the high supply rail and low supply rail, these amplifiers have efficiency above 90% and can be relatively compact and light, even for large power outputs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] For a few decades, industrial and military PWM amplifiers have been in common use, often for driving servomotors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Field-gradient coils in MRI machines are driven by relatively high-power PWM amplifiers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Historically, a crude form of PWM has been used to play back PCM digital sound on the PC speaker, which is driven by only two voltage levels, typically 0 and 5 V.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The Sega 32X uses PWM to play sample-based sound in its games.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] This method is used in the SACD format, and reproduction of the encoded audio signal is essentially similar to the method used in class-D amplifiers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] SPWM (sine–triangle pulse-width modulation) signals are used in solar inverter design.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] These switching signals are fed to the FETs that are used in the device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] The device's efficiency depends on the harmonic content of the PWM signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] There is much research on eliminating unwanted harmonics and improving the fundamental strength, some of which involves using a modified carrier signal instead of a classic sawtooth signal in order to decrease power losses and improve efficiency.
[src:hardware-interfaces/pulse-width-modulation] Another common application is in robotics where PWM signals are used to control the speed of the robot by controlling the motors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In telecommunications, **RS-232** or Recommended Standard 232 is a standard introduced in 1960 for serial communication transmission of data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] It formally defines signals connecting between a *DTE* (*data terminal equipment*) such as a computer terminal or PC, and a *DCE* (*data circuit-terminating equipment* or *data communication equipment*), such as a modem.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard defines the electrical characteristics and timing of signals, the meaning of signals, and the physical size and pinout of connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The current version of the standard is *TIA-232-F Interface Between Data Terminal Equipment and Data Circuit-Terminating Equipment Employing Serial Binary Data Interchange*, issued in 1997.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The RS-232 standard is commonly used with serial ports and serial cables.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] It is widely used in industrial communication devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A serial port complying with the RS-232 standard was once a standard feature of many types of computers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Personal computers used them for connections not only to modems, but also to printers, computer mice, data storage, uninterruptible power supplies, and other peripheral devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Compared with later interfaces such as RS-422, RS-485 and Ethernet, RS-232 has lower transmission speed, shorter maximum cable length, larger voltage swing, larger standard connectors, no multipoint capability and limited multidrop capability.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In modern personal computers, USB has displaced RS-232 from most of its peripheral interface roles.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Thanks to their simplicity and past ubiquity, however, RS-232 interfaces are still used—particularly in industrial CNC machines, networking equipment and scientific instruments where a short-range, point-to-point, low-speed wired data connection is fully adequate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard does not define such elements as the character encoding (i.e.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] ASCII, EBCDIC, or others), the framing of characters (start or stop bits, etc.), transmission order of bits, or error detection protocols.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The character format and transmission bit rate are set by the serial port hardware, typically a UART, which may also contain circuits to convert the internal logic levels to RS-232 compatible signal levels.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard does not define bit rates for transmission, except that it says it is intended for bit rates lower than 20,000 bits per second.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 was first introduced in 1960 by the Electronic Industries Association (EIA) as a *Recommended Standard*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The original DTEs were electromechanical teletypewriters, and the original DCEs were (usually) modems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When electronic terminals (smart and dumb) began to be used, they were often designed to be interchangeable with teletypewriters, and so supported RS-232.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Throughout the 1960s, the 232 Standard underwent a few iterations following the major innovations in computer and networking technology.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In October 1963, the EIA published its first revision, EIA RS-232-A.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This revision introduced iterative improvements including different connector types and different voltage ranges.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In October 1965, the EIA published EIA RS-232-B.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This revision increased the capacitance specifications to allow longer cable lengths and increase signal timing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] It also dropped the voltage from 25 Vpp to 15 Vpp.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In August of 1969, the EIA published EIA RS-232-C: *Interface Between Data Terminal Equipment and Data Communication Equipment Employing Serial Binary Data Interchange*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This revision dropped the voltage down to 12 Vpp and introduced the use of Data Communication Equipment (DCE) modems with the standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] As technology progressed, the RS-232 standard was starting to become obsolete.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In 1975, modifications to the RS-232 standard resulted in the creation of its supposed successor, the EIA RS-422 standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] However, as the RS-422 standard was being developed, the RS-232 standard was gaining popularity for use in computing, so the standard was updated to accommodate legacy systems and its continued usage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In 1981, the EIA dropped the Recommended Standard (RS) nomenclature for all of their published standards and republished the 232 standard as EIA-232-C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The revision included major changes including incorporating the DB-25 connector as part of the standard (it was only referenced in the appendix of RS-232-C), and setting the circuit capacitance limit to 2.5 nF.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In 1988, the Telecommunications Industry Association (TIA) was founded, as part of a merger of several organizations under the EIA.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In 1997, the Electronic Industries Association reorganized under the Electronics Industries Alliance, with the Telecommunications Industry Association serving as its subsidiary.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] That October, the TIA published *TIA ANSI/TIA/EIA-232-F: Interface between Data Terminal Equipment and Data Circuit-Terminating Equipment Employing Serial Binary Data Interchange*.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In 2002, the EIA delegated the standard entirely to the TIA, and Revision F was republished under TIA ANSI/TIA-232-F (R 2002), by the TR-30 Multi-Media Access, Protocols and Interfaces committee.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Following the dissolution of the Electronic Industries Alliance, the TIA reaffirmed the standard as TIA TIA-232-F (R 2012) in 2012 with no official changes or revisions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] No official changes have been made to the standard since.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Because RS-232 is used beyond the original purpose of interconnecting a terminal with a modem, successor standards have been developed to address the limitations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Because the standard did not foresee the requirements of devices such as computers, printers, test instruments, POS terminals, and so on, designers implementing an RS-232 compatible interface on their equipment often interpreted the standard idiosyncratically.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The resulting common problems were non-standard pin assignment of circuits on connectors, and incorrect or missing control signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The lack of adherence to the standards produced a thriving industry of breakout boxes, patch boxes, test equipment, books, and other aids for the connection of disparate equipment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A common deviation from the standard was to drive the signals at a reduced voltage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some manufacturers therefore built transmitters that supplied +5 V and −5 V and labeled them as "RS-232 compatible".
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In the book *PC 97 Hardware Design Guide*, Microsoft deprecated support for the RS-232 compatible serial port of the original IBM PC design.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Today, RS-232 has mostly been replaced in personal computers by USB for local communications.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Advantages compared to RS-232 are that USB is faster, uses lower voltages, and has connectors that are simpler to connect and use.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Disadvantages of USB compared to RS-232 are that USB is more susceptible to electromagnetic interference (EMI) and that maximum cable length defined by standards is much shorter (15 meters for RS-232 versus 3–5 meters for USB, depending on the USB version and use of active cables).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 cable lengths of 2000 meters are possible with appropriate line drivers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In fields such as laboratory automation or surveying, RS-232 devices continue to be used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some types of programmable logic controllers, variable-frequency drives, servo drives, and computerized numerical control equipment are programmable via RS-232.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Computer manufacturers have responded to this demand by re-introducing the DE-9M connector on their computers or by making adapters available.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 ports are also commonly used to communicate to headless systems such as servers, where no monitor or keyboard is installed, during boot when an operating system is not yet running and therefore no network connection is possible.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A computer with an RS-232 serial port can communicate with the serial port of an embedded system (such as a router) as an alternative to monitoring over Ethernet.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Personal computers (and other devices) also made use of the standard so that they could connect to existing equipment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] For many years, an RS-232-compatible port was a standard feature for serial communications, such as modem connections, on many computers (with the computer acting as the DTE).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] It remained in widespread use into the late 1990s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In personal computer peripherals, it has largely been supplanted by other interface standards, such as USB.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 is still used to connect older designs of peripherals, industrial equipment (such as PLCs), console ports, and special purpose equipment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In RS-232, user data is sent as a time-series of bits.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Both synchronous and asynchronous transmissions are supported by the standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In addition to the data circuits, the standard defines a number of control circuits used to manage the connection between the DTE and DCE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Each data or control circuit only operates in one direction, that is, signaling from a DTE to the attached DCE or the reverse.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Because transmit data and receive data are separate circuits, the interface can operate in a full duplex manner, supporting concurrent data flow in both directions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard does not define character framing within the data stream or character encoding.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The RS-232 standard defines the voltage levels that correspond to logical one and logical zero levels for the data transmission and the control signal lines.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Valid signals are either in the range of +3 to +15 volts or the range −3 to −15 volts with respect to the "Common Ground" (GND) pin; consequently, the range between −3 and +3 volts is not a valid RS-232 level.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] For data transmission lines (TxD, RxD, and their secondary channel equivalents), logic one is represented as a negative voltage and the signal condition is called "mark".
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Logic zero is signaled with a positive voltage and the signal condition is termed "space".
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Control signals have the opposite polarity: the asserted or active state is positive voltage and the de-asserted or inactive state is negative voltage.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Examples of control lines include request to send (RTS), clear to send (CTS), data terminal ready (DTR), and data set ready (DSR).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard specifies a maximum open-circuit voltage of 25 volts: signal levels of ±5 V, ±10 V, ±12 V, and ±15 V are all commonly seen depending on the voltages available to the line driver circuit.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Many RS-232 driver chips have inbuilt charge pump circuitry to produce the required voltages from a 3 or 5 volt supply.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 drivers and receivers must be able to withstand indefinite short circuits to the ground or to any voltage level up to ±25 volts.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The slew rate, or how fast the signal changes between levels, is also controlled.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Because the voltage levels are higher than logic levels typically used by integrated circuits, special intervening driver circuits are required to translate logic levels.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] These also protect the device's internal circuitry from short circuits or transients that may appear on the RS-232 interface, and provide sufficient current to comply with the slew rate requirements for data transmission.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Because both ends of the RS-232 circuit depend on the ground pin being zero volts, problems will occur when connecting machinery and computers where the voltage between the ground pin on one end, and the ground pin on the other is not zero.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This may also cause a hazardous ground loop.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Use of a common ground limits RS-232 to applications with relatively short cables.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] If the two devices are far enough apart or on separate power systems, the local ground connections at either end of the cable will have differing voltages; this difference will reduce the noise margin of the signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Balanced, differential serial connections such as RS-422 or RS-485 can tolerate larger ground voltage differences because of the differential signaling.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Unused interface signals terminated to the ground will have an undefined logic state.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Where it is necessary to permanently set a control signal to a defined state, it must be connected to a voltage source that asserts the logic 1 or logic 0 levels, for example with a pull-up resistor.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some devices provide test voltages on their interface connectors for this purpose.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-232 devices may be classified as Data Terminal Equipment (DTE) or Data Circuit-terminating Equipment (DCE); this defines at each device which wires will be sending and receiving each signal.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] According to the standard, male connectors have DTE pin functions, and female connectors have DCE pin functions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Other devices may have any combination of connector gender and pin definitions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Many terminals were manufactured with female connectors but were sold with a cable with male connectors at each end; the terminal with its cable satisfied the recommendations in the standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard recommends the D-subminiature 25-pin connector up to revision C, and makes it mandatory as of revision D.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Most devices only implement a few of the twenty signals specified in the standard, so connectors and cables with fewer pins are sufficient for most connections, more compact, and less expensive.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Personal computer manufacturers replaced the DB-25M connector with the smaller DE-9M connector.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This connector, with a different pinout (see Serial port pinouts), is prevalent for personal computers and associated devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Presence of a 25-pin D-sub connector does not necessarily indicate an RS-232-C compliant interface.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] For example, on the original IBM PC, a male D-sub was an RS-232-C DTE port (with a non-standard current loop interface on reserved pins), but the female D-sub connector on the same PC model was used for the parallel "Centronics" printer port.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some personal computers put non-standard voltages or signals on some pins of their serial ports.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The standard does not define a maximum cable length, but instead defines the maximum capacitance that a compliant drive circuit must tolerate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A widely used rule of thumb indicates that cables more than 15 m (50 ft) long will have too much capacitance, unless special cables are used.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] By using low-capacitance cables, communication can be maintained over larger distances up to about 300 m (1,000 ft).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] For longer distances, other signal standards, such as RS-422, are better suited for higher speeds.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Since the standard definitions are not always correctly applied, it is often necessary to consult documentation, test connections with a breakout box, or use trial and error to find a cable that works when interconnecting two devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Connecting a fully standard-compliant DCE device and DTE device would use a cable that connects identical pin numbers in each connector (a so-called "straight cable").
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] "Gender changers" are available to solve gender mismatches between cables and connectors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Connecting devices with different types of connectors requires a cable that connects the corresponding pins according to the table below.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Cables with 9 pins on one end and 25 on the other are common.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Manufacturers of equipment with 8P8C connectors usually provide a cable with either a DB-25 or DE-9 connector (or sometimes interchangeable connectors so they can work with multiple devices).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Poor-quality cables can cause false signals by crosstalk between data and control lines (such as Ring Indicator).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] If a given cable will not allow a data connection, especially if a gender changer is in use, a null modem cable may be necessary.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Gender changers and null modem cables are not mentioned in the standard, so there is no officially sanctioned design for them.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The following table lists commonly used RS-232 signals (called "circuits" in the specifications) and their pin assignments on the recommended DB-25 connectors (see Serial port pinouts for other commonly used connectors not defined by the standard).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The signals are named from the standpoint of the DTE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The ground pin is a common return for the other connections, and establishes the "zero" voltage to which voltages on the other pins are referenced.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The DB-25 connector includes a second "protective ground" on pin 1; this is connected internally to equipment frame ground, and should not be connected in the cable or connector to signal ground.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] On an external modem the status of the Ring Indicator pin is often coupled to the "AA" (auto answer) light, which flashes if the RI signal has detected a ring.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The asserted RI signal follows the ringing pattern closely, which can permit software to detect distinctive ring patterns.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The Ring Indicator signal is used by some older uninterruptible power supplies (UPSs) to signal a power failure state to the computer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Certain personal computers can be configured for wake-on-ring, allowing a computer that is suspended to answer a phone call.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The Request to Send (RTS) and Clear to Send (CTS) signals were originally defined for use with half-duplex (one direction at a time) modems such as the Bell 202.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] These modems disable their transmitters when not required and must transmit a synchronization preamble to the receiver when they are re-enabled.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The DTE asserts RTS to indicate a desire to transmit to the DCE, and in response the DCE asserts CTS to grant permission, once synchronization with the DCE at the far end is achieved.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Such modems are no longer in common use.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] There is no corresponding signal that the DTE could use to temporarily halt incoming data from the DCE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Thus RS-232's use of the RTS and CTS signals, per the older versions of the standard, is asymmetric.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This scheme is also employed in present-day RS-232 to RS-485 converters.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] RS-485 is a multiple-access bus on which only one device can transmit at a time, a concept that is not provided for in RS-232.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The RS-232 device asserts RTS to tell the converter to take control of the RS-485 bus so that the converter, and thus the RS-232 device, can send data onto the bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Modern communications environments use full-duplex (both directions simultaneously) modems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In that environment, DTEs have no reason to deassert RTS.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] However, due to the possibility of changing line quality, delays in processing of data, etc., there is a need for symmetric, bidirectional flow control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A symmetric alternative providing flow control in both directions was developed and marketed in the late 1980s by various equipment manufacturers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] It redefined the RTS signal to mean that the DTE is ready to receive data from the DCE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This scheme was eventually codified in version RS-232-E (actually TIA-232-E by that time) by defining a new signal, "RTR (Ready to Receive)", which is CCITT V.24 circuit 133.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] TIA-232-E and the corresponding international standards were updated to show that circuit 133, when implemented, shares the same pin as RTS (Request to Send), and that when 133 is in use, RTS is assumed by the DCE to be asserted at all times.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] In this scheme, commonly called "RTS/CTS flow control" or "RTS/CTS handshaking" (though the technically correct name would be "RTR/CTS"), the DTE asserts RTS whenever it is ready to receive data from the DCE, and the DCE asserts CTS whenever it is ready to receive data from the DTE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Unlike the original use of RTS and CTS with half-duplex modems, these two signals operate independently from one another.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This is an example of hardware flow control.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] However, "hardware flow control" in the description of the options available on an RS-232-equipped device does not always mean RTS/CTS handshaking.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Equipment using this protocol must be prepared to buffer some extra data, since the remote system may have begun transmitting just before the local system de-asserts RTR.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A minimal "3-wire" RS-232 connection consisting only of transmit data, receive data, and ground, is commonly used when the full facilities of RS-232 are not required.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Even a two-wire connection (data and ground) can be used if the data flow is one way (for example, a digital postal scale that periodically sends a weight reading, or a GPS receiver that periodically sends position, if no configuration via RS-232 is necessary).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When only hardware flow control is required in addition to two-way data, the RTS and CTS lines are added in a 5-wire version.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The EIA-232 standard specifies connections for several features that are not used in most implementations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Their use requires 25-pin connectors and cables.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The DTE or DCE can specify use of a "high" or "low" signaling rate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The rates, as well as which device will select the rate, must be configured in both the DTE and DCE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The prearranged device selects the high rate by setting the Data Signal Rate Selector (DSRS, pin 23) signal to ON.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Sometimes called Data Rate Select (DRS), this signal should not be confused with the more commonly used Data Set Ready (DSR, pin 6).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Many DCE devices have a loopback capability used for testing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When enabled, signals are echoed back to the sender rather than being sent on to the receiver.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] If supported, the DTE can signal the local DCE (the one it is connected to) to enter loopback mode by setting Local Loop (LL, pin 18) to ON, or the remote DCE (the one the local DCE is connected to) to enter loopback mode by setting Remote Loop (RL, pin 21) to ON.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The latter tests the communications link, as well as both DCEs.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When the DCE is in test mode, it signals the DTE by setting Test Indicator (TI, pin 25) to ON.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A commonly used version of loopback testing does not involve any special capability of either end.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A hardware loopback is simply a wire connecting complementary pins together in the same connector (see *loopback*).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Loopback testing is often performed with a specialized DTE called a bit error rate tester (or BERT).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some synchronous devices provide a clock signal to synchronize data transmission, especially at higher data rates.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Two timing signals are provided by the DCE.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Pin 15 is the transmitter clock (TCK), or send timing (ST); the DTE puts the next bit on the transmit data line (pin 2) when this clock transitions from OFF to ON (so it is stable during the ON to OFF transition when the DCE registers the bit).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Pin 17 is the receiver clock (RCK), or receive timing (RT); the DTE reads the next bit from the receive data line (pin 3) when this clock transitions from ON to OFF.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Alternatively, the DTE can provide a clock signal, called transmitter timing (TT, pin 24) for transmitted data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Data is changed when the clock transitions from OFF to ON, and read during the ON to OFF transition.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] TT can be used to overcome the problem of propagation delay in a long cable.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] ST must traverse a cable of unknown length and delay, clock a bit out of the DTE after another unknown delay, and return it to the DCE over the same unknown cable delay.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When sending data at high speed, the data bit may not arrive in time for the ON to OFF transition of ST.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Since the relation between the transmitted bit and TT can be fixed in the DTE design, and since both signals traverse the same cable length, using TT eliminates the issue.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] TT may be generated by looping ST back with an appropriate phase change to align it with the transmitted data.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] ST loop back to TT lets the DTE use the DCE as the frequency reference, and correct the clock to data timing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Synchronous clocking is required for such protocols as SDLC, HDLC, and X.25.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A secondary data channel, identical in capability to the primary channel, can optionally be implemented by the DTE and DCE devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Other serial signaling standards may not interoperate with standard-compliant RS-232 ports.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] For example, using the TTL levels of near +5 V and 0 V puts the mark level in the undefined area of the standard.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Such levels are sometimes used with NMEA 0183-compliant GPS receivers and depth finders.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A chip such as MAX232 is required to convert the voltage levels.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A 20 mA current loop uses the absence of 20 mA current for high, and the presence of current in the loop for low; this signaling method is often used for long-distance and optically isolated links.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Connection of a current-loop device to a compliant RS-232 port requires a level translator.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Current-loop devices can supply voltages in excess of the must-withstand voltage limits of a compliant device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The original IBM PC serial port card implemented a 20 mA current-loop interface, which was never emulated by other suppliers of plug-compatible equipment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] The International Telecommunication Union publishes standard ITR-R V.24 (formerly CCITT standard V.24), "List of Definitions for Interchange Circuits between Data Terminal Equipment (DTE) and Data Circuit-Terminating Equipment (DCE)" with circuit definitions compatible to those in EIA RS 232.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] V.24 does not specify signal levels or timing.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Electrical parameters for signals are specified in ITU-R-V.28.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] When developing or troubleshooting systems using RS-232, close examination of hardware signals can be important to find problems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] This can be done using simple devices with LEDs that indicate the logic levels of data and control signals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] "Y" cables may be used to allow using another serial port to monitor all traffic on one direction.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] A serial line analyzer is a device similar to a logic analyzer but specialized for RS-232's voltage levels, connectors, and, where used, clock signals; it collects, stores, and displays the data and control signals, allowing developers to view them in detail.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Some simply display the signals as waveforms; more elaborate versions include the ability to decode characters in ASCII or other common codes and to interpret common protocols used over RS-232 such as SDLC, HDLC, DDCMP, and X.25.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-232] Serial line analyzers are available as standalone units, as software and interface cables for general-purpose logic analyzers and oscilloscopes, and as programs that run on common personal computers and devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 supports inexpensive local networks and multidrop communications links, using the same differential signaling over twisted pair as RS-422.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It is generally accepted that RS-485 can be used with data rates up to 10 Mbit/s or, at lower speeds, distances up to 1,200 m (4,000 ft).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] As a rule of thumb, the speed in bit/s multiplied by the length in meters should not exceed 108.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Thus a 50-meter cable should not signal faster than 2 Mbit/s.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] In contrast to RS-422, which has a driver circuit which cannot be switched off, RS-485 drivers use three-state logic allowing individual transmitters to be deactivated.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] This allows RS-485 to implement linear bus topologies using only two wires.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The equipment located along a set of RS-485 wires are interchangeably called nodes, stations or devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The recommended arrangement of the wires is as a connected series of point-to-point (multidropped) nodes, i.e. a line or bus, not a star, ring, or multiply connected network.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Star and ring topologies are not recommended because of signal reflections or excessively low or high termination impedance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] If a star configuration is unavoidable, special RS-485 repeaters are available which bidirectionally listen for data on each span and then retransmit the data onto all other spans.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Ideally, the two ends of the cable will have a termination resistor connected across the two wires.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Without termination resistors, signal reflections off the unterminated end of the cable can cause data corruption.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Termination resistors also reduce electrical noise sensitivity due to the lower impedance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The value of each termination resistor should be equal to the cable characteristic impedance (typically, 120 ohms for twisted pairs).
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The termination also includes pull up and pull down resistors to establish bias for each data wire for the case when the lines are not being driven by any device.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] This way, the lines will be biased to known voltages and nodes will not interpret the noise from undriven lines as actual data; without biasing resistors, the data lines float in such a way that electrical noise sensitivity is greatest when all device stations are silent or unpowered.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The EIA once labeled all its standards with the prefix RS (Recommended Standard), but the EIA/TIA officially replaced RS with EIA/TIA to help identify the origin of its standards.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The EIA has officially disbanded and the standard is now maintained by the TIA as TIA-485, but engineers and applications guides continue to use the RS-485 designation.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The initial edition of EIA RS-485 was dated April 1983.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 only specifies the electrical characteristics of the generator and the receiver: the physical layer.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It does not specify or recommend any communications protocol; Other standards define the protocols for communication over an RS-485 link.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The foreword to the standard references *The Telecommunications Systems Bulletin TSB-89* which contains application guidelines, including data signaling rate vs. cable length, stub length, and configurations.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Section 4 defines the electrical characteristics of the generator (transmitter or driver), receiver, transceiver, and system.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] These characteristics include: definition of a unit load, voltage ranges, open-circuit voltages, thresholds, and transient tolerance.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It also defines three generator interface points (signal lines); A, B and C.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] This section also defines the logic states 1 (off) and 0 (on), by the polarity between A and B terminals.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] If A is negative with respect to B, the state is binary 1.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The reversed polarity (A positive with respect to B) is binary 0.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The standard does not assign any logic function to the two states.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485, like RS-422, can be made full-duplex by using four wires.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Since RS-485 is a multi-point specification, however, this is not necessary or desirable in many cases.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 and RS-422 can interoperate with certain restrictions.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Converters between RS-485 and RS-232 are available to allow a personal computer to communicate with remote devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] By using repeaters very large RS-485 networks can be formed.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] TSB-89A, Application Guidelines for TIA/EIA-485-A does not recommend using star topology, as doing so may lead to long stubs (branches of the star), which can cause signal reflections that make data transmission unreliable.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 does not define a communication protocol; merely an electrical interface.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Although many applications use RS-485 signal levels, the speed, format, and protocol of the data transmission are not specified by RS-485.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Interoperability of even similar devices from different manufacturers is not assured by compliance with the signal levels alone.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 signals are used in a wide range of computer and automation systems.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] In a computer system, SCSI-2 and SCSI-3 may use RS-485 to implement the physical layer for data transmission between a controller and a disk drive.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 is used for low-speed data communications in commercial aircraft cabins' vehicle bus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It requires minimal wiring and can share the wiring among several seats, reducing weight.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] These are used in programmable logic controllers and on factory floors.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 is used as the physical layer underlying many standard and proprietary automation protocols used to implement industrial control systems, including the most common versions of Modbus and Profibus.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] **DH 485** is a proprietary communications protocol used by Allen-Bradley in their line of industrial control units.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Utilizing a series of dedicated interface devices, it allows PCs and industrial controllers to communicate.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Since it is differential, it resists electromagnetic interference from motors and welding equipment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] In theatre and performance venues, RS-485 networks are used to control lighting and other systems using the DMX512 protocol.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 serves as a physical layer for the AES3 digital audio interconnect.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] RS-485 is also used in building automation as the simple bus wiring and long cable length is ideal for joining remote devices.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It may be used to control video surveillance systems or to interconnect security control panels and devices such as access control card readers.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] It is also used in Digital Command Control (DCC) for model railways.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] The external interface to the DCC command station is often RS-485 used by hand-held controllers or for controlling the layout in a networked PC environment.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] 8P8C modular connectors are used in this case.
[src:hardware-interfaces/rs-485] Because a mark (logic 1) condition is traditionally represented (e.g. in RS-232) with a negative voltage; and space (logic 0) represented with a positive one, A may be considered the *non-inverting* signal and B as inverting.
